The paper deals with secure multiparty computation of election results, which is a topic that falls under the category of cryptography and security (cs.CR). The paper also involves the use of algorithms and data structures for tallying and computing election results, which falls under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also involves the use of information theory for preserving privacy and secrecy, which falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT). The paper also involves the use of communication complexity for designing the protocols, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper also involves the use of machine learning for analyzing the protocols' compliance with desiderata, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG).
